An incredibly powerful character trait is to be able to argue with those you love, care for, or even just work with, only to then act as if nothing happened the next day. I was taught this observing my father and the men who prioritised what's most important. If I were to receive a lecture or be severely disciplined, I'd expect to be in disgrace for a while due to my uneducated, inexperienced mind. Upon sitting in the car or reaching the warehouse, I'd see a man who got on with the day as if nothing happened. This instantly, subliminally, told me to be grateful and follow by example rather than pretend I was entitled to remain stroppy. To learn the importance of harsh words as well as their lack of importance compared to actions is a fine skill embraced by few. The respect and lessons given to me as a result were firmly carried with me into adulthood. It would then shock me to see that many people in my life held grudges over trivial issues or due to the lessons they should have learnt from. In turn, instead of appreciation of such a character trait, many confuse it for submitting or admitting to wrongdoing as opposed to stoic forgiveness. To this day I see so many people who miss the brilliance of such individuals, including the standards set by my father. Those with the eyes to see, see someone to admire. It dawned on me that they'd never had such examples given to them, and so, for the rest of their lives, they'll confuse who and what's truly important.

Perched atop the luxe co-op residences at 1500 N. Lake Shore Dr., encompassing the entire 24th and 25th floors overlooking Lake Michigan, this spectacular residence boasts 8,000 sq ft of interior living space and 5,000 sq ft of private outdoor space, including a massive, east-facing terrace with a lawn, manicured gardens, a Roman fountain, and fabulous city and lake views. The building itself is a Chicago institution. Built in 1927 and designed by New York architect Rosario Candela with Chicago firm McNally & Quinn, the building has been home to many prominent Chicago families over the years. The penthouse, however, was built especially for the building's original owner, and has rarely changed hands in the last century. World-class, artisan details like stained glass windows, stone friezes, hand-carved wood doors, and original bronze hardware are found throughout, beginning with a private entry foyer that connects to a 39'-long, walnut-paneled gallery hall with vaulted, hand-frescoed ceilings. The living and entertaining footprint on the main level features a formal dining room, a showpiece living room, a handsome bar/lounge, two offices, a modern chef's kitchen, and three amazing terraces. The living room stuns with 20'-high, coffered ceilings, and a stone fireplace, and affords access to both the yard and the north terrace. The kitchen flaunts custom cabinetry, professional grade appliances, a marble-topped island and counters, and an informal dining area. Four of the home's bedrooms currently live on the main level as well, each with its own unique footprint and architectural details. There's also a spacious, lake-facing room with its own private patio with lounge and fire pit, two generous closets, and a custom, marble-clad en-suite bath that could serve as a stunning primary suite or an epic family room. The home's original limestone staircases have been beautifully preserved, and lead to the second level via three access points. Here, a sixth en-suite bedroom, a sauna room, and more flexible space reside. Plus, there's a partial third floor with a game room/bar and additional storage spaces. White-glove building amenities include a full-time door staff, an on-site manager, and a live-in engineer. This property includes valet parking and pets are welcome. With pedigree and proximity to Lincoln Park, the lakefront, and the best of Chicago's first-class dining and shopping, the penthouse at 1500 N. Lake Shore Dr. is uncompromising, luxury living at its finest. When I was young I felt comfort within the simple design of my grandparents homes. Today, instead of such homely comfort, we're surrounded by the hellish nature of modernistic decors. You may have once been bored, or unimpressed, by the simplistic nature of old fashioned homes. But, the truth is, you was truly at home. We've been led to believe that we're past such out-dated design, when in reality, our subconscious yearns for it's return. Those of you with relatives who are old enough to possess such homes will know of rooms without a scrap of technology. Gifted instead, with a smell and a feel of a wholesome, culturally significant dwelling. That smell, like the feeling that comes with it, will soon disappear altogether, alongside the designs we've selfishly left behind. The next time you're in a hurry to leave, or ready to dismiss the interior designs of our recent ancestors, remember that any day now, we shall see, smell, feel, love, and know their like no more.

Glastening was named after a Welsh chieftain named Cyndrwyn Glas(t) (i.e. ‚Äúthe grey‚Äù), son of Elnaw, who hailed from the chiefdom of Dogfeiling in north Wales, which was part of the Kingdom of Gwynedd. He was a descendant of Gwynedd‚Äôs founder, Cunedda Wledig, who hailed from Manaw Gododdin in Scotland. üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å≥Û†Å£Û†Å¥Û†Åøüè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å∑Û†Å¨Û†Å≥Û†Åø After the Welsh king of Powys, Selyf Sarffgadau (‚ÄúSolomon Battle-Serpent‚Äù) was killed by the Angles of Northumbria at the Battle of Chester (AD 613), Cyndrwyn seems to have opportunistically invaded Powys and enthroned his son Elfan there. Part of Powys‚Äô territory in central England was carved out to form another kingdom called Pengwern, where Cyndrwyn‚Äôs other son Cynddylan was enthroned. Another son, Morfael, gained renown fighting against the Angles of Mercia, when he stormed and took the town of Caer-Luitcoyt (now Lichfield) from them. Subsequently, an alliance was made with Penda of Mercia, and the Pengwern Welsh were instrumental in the defeat and killing of king Oswald of Northumbria at the Battle of Maserfield (AD 642). However, king Penda‚Äôs Welsh allies would eventually have a falling out with him, and they notably abstained from fighting the Battle of Winwaed (AD 655), where he was killed by Oswiu of Northumbria. The victorious Oswiu then attacked Pengwern unexpectedly, killing Cynddylan and Elfan, and forcing the elderly Cyndrwyn, his son Morfael, and many of their people to seek refuge in Dumnonia. There, they were apparently given Glastening as a chiefdom. Tragically, they lost half of it almost immediately, as the West Saxons invaded and defeated the Britons at the Battle of Peonnum (AD 658), pushing the border to the river Parrett. "It is a deplorable fact that the religion of our forefathers seems to be but little cared for in this country. The mythologies of other nations every student manifests an interest for. He reads with the greatest zeal all the legends of Rome and Greece, of India and China. He is familiar with every room in the labyrinth of Crete, while when he is introduced to the shining halls of Valhal and Gladsheim he gropes his way like a blind man. He does not know that Idun, with her beautiful apples, might, if applied to, render even greater services than Ariadne with her wonderful thread. When we inquire whom Tuesday and Wednesday and Thursday and Friday are named after, and press questions in reference to Tyr, Odin, Thor and Freyja, we get at best but a wise and knowing look. Are we, then, as a nation, like the ancient Jews, and do we bend the knee before the gods of foreign nations and forsake the altars of our own gods? What if we then should suffer the fate of that unhappy people‚Äîbe scattered over all the world and lose our fatherland? In these Eddas our fathers have bequeathed unto us all their profoundest, all their sublimest, all their best thought. They are the concentrated result of their greatest intellectual and spiritual effort, and it behooves us to cherish this treasure and make it the fountain at which the whole American branch of the Yggdrasil ash may imbibe a united national sentiment. It is not enough to brush the dust off these gods and goddesses of our ancestors and put them up on pedestals as ornaments in our museums and libraries. These coins of the past are not to be laid away in numismatic collections. The grandson must use what he has inherited from his grandfather. If the coin is not intelligible, then it will have to be sent to the mint and stamped anew, in order that it may circulate freely. Our ancestral deities want a place in our hearts and in our songs." Prof. Rasmus B Anderson - A Norwegian-American in 1879

Photo of "teach an alais" (sweathouses, literally, in Irish). Shown, Cleighran More, county Leitrim, beside a stream for plunges. Irish Sweathouses are small, rare, beehive-shaped, corbelled structures of field-stones, rarely more than 2 metres in external height and diameter, with very small "creep" entrances which may have been blocked by clothing, or by temporary doors of peat-turves, or whatever came to hand. Most of those which survive could not have accommodated more than three or four sweaters. They resemble the small 'caves', built into banks, in which many Irish natives were reported to live in the seventeenth century. They were often covered with sods of earth to counterweight and stabilise the corbelling, and these would also have acted as insulation after firing. That they were fired is certain, for soot remains on the ceilings of some. Catharine Gage, wife of the Reverend Robert Gage of Rathlin Island (between county Antrim and the Mull of Kintyre in Scotland), wrote:- 'Small buildings called sweat-houses are erected, somewhat in the shape of a beehive, constructed with stones and turf, neatly put together; the roof being formed of the same material, with a small hole in the centre. There is also an aperture below, just large enough to admit one person, on hands and knees. When required for use, a large fire is lighted in the middle of the floor, and allowed to burn out, by which time the house has become thoroughly heated; the ashes are then swept away, and the patient goes in, having first taken off his clothes, with the exception of his undergarment, which he hands to a friend outside. The hole in the roof is then covered with a flat stone and the entrance is also closed up with sods, to prevent the admission of air. The patient remains within until he begins to perspire copiously, when (if young and strong) he plunges into the sea, but the aged or weak retire to bed for a few hours.' [Gage: A History of the Island of Rathlin, 1851] üáÆüá™ @europeanvolk

cleaned_message: The Thorsberg moor, located near S√ºderbrarup in Anglia, Schleswig-Holstein, Germany, is known for its significant archaeological finds from the Roman Iron Age. One of these discoveries is a 4th-century Germanic tunic, which is an important piece of early clothing. This tunic was found in the moor and is made of wool. It provides valuable insights into the clothing styles and textile manufacturing techniques of the Germanic tribes during the 4th century. The tunic is well-preserved, allowing researchers to study its construction and design in detail. The Thorsberg tunic is now housed in the Gottorp Palace in Schleswig, Germany. cleaned_message: The tale of #Medusa is in fact one of great tragedy. Medusa had been admired for her beauty within Athens, Greece. A person who was kind and obeyed the Greek gods of the time. Her love for 'Athena Goddess of War' led her to becoming the priestess of Athena‚Äôs temple, a role unimaginable by the standards of mono-theism. Men from far and wide would travel to gaze upon her beauty until she became a symbol of beauty itself. Medusa's beauty became so renowned it made Athena herself jealous. Poseidon 'God of the Sea' had been seeking Medusa's affection, but faced rejection due to her wanting to remain pure. Poseidon, eventually took Medusa by force, whilst Athena did nothing to protect her. Poseidon would rape Medusa and then leaver her stranded with her image in utter ruin. As Medusa was no longer pure, Athena used the excuse to curse Medusa for the sins she could have prevented. Medusa‚Äôs once beautiful hair, was turned into a head of venomous snakes. And to ensure no man may look upon her again, Medusa‚Äôs eyes, would turn those who looked at them to stone. Medusa couldn‚Äôt even look into anyone‚Äôs eyes, never mind seek some kind of comfort. Medusa was also unable to turn herself into stone, and so the men who once admired her, strove to end her life for glory. Medusa was forced to hide and fight off her attackers until Zeus 'King of Gods' ordered his son Perseus to behead what was now considered a monster. The injustice of this story is a great lesson of hardship and misfortune from the ancient world. Unlike many other stories or religious scripture, many tales of the 'Old Gods' are but ways to explain our fear and pain as opposed to a story with a just ending. For years the tale of Medusa seems to be told as a form of heroism as opposed to tragedy, but for those who know the full detail of this story, it's a touching tragedy of a woman, as opposed to the heroic victory of a man.

Likely Normans Location: Tongwynlais, De Cymru (South) Native/Non-Native: Non-Native Year Built: 11th-13th Century, rebuilt in 19th Century Overseer: Cadw Nestled in the woodlands of Tongwynlais, near Cardiff, Castell Coch is a picturesque, fairy-tale castle that captures the imagination. Originally built in the 13th century on the remains of a 12th-century castle, it was transformed in the 19th century into the romantic, turreted masterpiece that stands today. Its vivid interiors and captivating architecture make it a must-visit for history and fantasy enthusiasts alike. It is believed by many that the castle was first built during or following the Norman Invasion of Cymru. Like many non-native castles of the day, it was built to suppress the local Welsh populations and ensure there were Norman forces present in the south. It was also one of the castles to switch hands on multiple occasions, with the native Welsh seizing it more than once during the high middle-ages. In the centuries since, it had been a property of the Bute family; home to a vineyard and a scenic movie/TV location used in Doctor Who and The Worst Witch. It is now a known renowned tourist and even more popular marriage destination in Cymru. üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å∑Û†Å¨Û†Å≥Û†Åø @europeanvolk

20 April 1889 ‚Ä¶ a labourer planting potatoes finds a Late Roman hoard of treasure at Szil√°gysomly√≥ (in what is now SÃ¶imleu Silvaniei, Romania). This is the second hoard to be found here. The first, probably buried by the same person in the early 5th Century, was discovered by two shepherd boys back in 1797. This second hoard - the one discovered in 1889 - includes fibulae (large brooches) decorated with gold and jewels, an oath-swearing ring and three gold bowls. The highlight however is a magnificent golden fibula weighing 0.5kg. The stone at the centre is a perfect oval-shaped onyx, highlighted by rock crystal, carnelian, garnet and coloured glass (top left photo). These massive brooches were worn as a sign of rank by the men of the Roman imperial family in the 4th Century AD. The top right photo shows one of these brooches as worn by the Emperor Valentinian II (375-392). To date, the Szil√°gysomly√≥ jewel is the only imperial fibula known in existence. Most likely the brooch was made in an imperial workshop and then presented in the 4th Century to an important ‚Äòbarbarian‚Äô ruler: given the find location, probably a Gepid prince in the Carpathian Basin. The treasure was probably hidden in the early 5th Century, as the Gepids fought - unsuccessfully - to preserve their independence from Attila and his Huns. üá∑üá¥ @europeanvolk

Roman Boiler; The first testimonies of the Villa Della Pisanella date back to November 1868, when Modestino Pulzella, while tracing the foundations of a wall, found some pre-existing wall structures. Continuing the excavations, some mosaics were found. The excavations then had to stop because the owner of the neighboring land, Vincenzo De Prisco, highlighted the danger of damage to his land. Only in September 1894 were excavations resumed, which continued until June 1895. This time precisely at the initiative of De Prisco who, evidently, no longer feared "damage." in May 1896 the Roman baths and boiler came to light, found intact, with all their pipes. De Prisco then carried out the restoration of part of the villa, transforming it into a kind of museum (before it was decided to rebury it). And it is precisely during the life of the ‚ÄúMuseo De Prisco‚Äù that the Alinari Brothers had the opportunity to take this extraordinary photo. The boiler was equipped with real taps to regulate the flow of water. The valves were of the male type: the upper cylinder was then inserted into the valve body and, by piercing it, it closed and opened the flow of water with a 90 degree rotation. The production of this type of mechanisms by the Collegia Fabrorum had to comply with precisely established standards, similar to those defined today by the EU, which we know through the work of Frontinus: De aquae ductu urbis Romae. The boiler and pipes were made of lead but the valves were made of bronze and cast in a single block using molds. The connection to the lead pipes was made by soldering. Instead of the blowtorch, small flat-tipped rods (a type of screwdriver) were used, the tips of which had been heated to red hot thanks to the use of portable forges. Additionally, a solder wire with a 70% lead alloy was used. For the flux (the product that favors the distribution of the new metal on the surface to be soldered, protecting it from oxidation) pine resin was probably used. üáÆüáπ @europeanvolk

All of them come from Vindolanda, a Roman fort right by Hadrian‚Äôs Wall. They were preserved in anaerobic bog-like conditions, so what you‚Äôre about to hear are real Roman soldiers from the 1st to 2nd century AD, nearly 2,000 years ago. cleaned_message: Germanic fibulae from the early 5th century are fascinating artifacts that provide a glimpse into the art and culture of the time. These brooches, often found in the Kunsthistorisches Museum in Vienna, are a testament to the intricate craftsmanship of the Germanic tribes during the Migration Period. The Roman Empire was on the brink of collapse in the 3rd century, and its army was becoming increasingly Germanic. When the Huns pushed these tribes westward in the 4th century, they spilled across the Empire‚Äôs borders and began to settle there. These fibulae were not just decorative but also functional, used to fasten garments. The designs varied, with some shaped like eagles and made of sheet gold over bronze. They were commonly found in barbarian graves, reflecting their popularity during the early Middle Ages. The term ‚Äúbarbarian‚Äù comes from the Greek word ‚Äúbarbaros‚Äù, meaning ‚Äúforeign‚Äù, and is often used as a blanket term for the non-Roman groups who migrated into western Europe. The fibulae serve as a reminder of these migrations and the cultural exchanges that occurred during this tumultuous period in history. @europeanvolk

The first modern flushable toilet was invented in 1596 by Sir John Harrington. He installed one for his godmother, Queen Elizabeth I. His invention included a water tank and a flush valve. If you were fortunate and born into considerable wealth, you might have used a garderobe (derived from the French word for "wardrobe"). The Stone Ship in Blomsholm, is one of the oldest in Sweden, dating from the early Scandinavian Iron Age, around 400 - 600 AD. The ship is more than 40 meters long and consists of 49 stones. The stones amidships are 1 meter high, while the ones in the bow and stern are over 4 meters high. The size and prominent position of the grave indicate that an important person must be buried here. The Stone Ship is located on a grave field, which is the most known ancient monument at Blomsholm. The area is rich in ancient remains from the Stone Age until medieval times, making it one of Bohusl√§n's finest cultural heritage landscapes. There are also several other large megaliths in the area, including another stone circle and menhirs from the Neolithic age. The monuments at the grave fields in Blomsholm were a symbol of power and wealth, indicating that the area was a powerful center at the time. The Stone Ship's location, where the route of E6 is located today, was once a sailing route for merchant ships between Oslo and Copenhagen. The Stone Ship and other monuments at Blomsholm represent the extensive trading activities that took place in the area. The greatness of Blomsholm ended sometime during the seventh century. Today, a walking trail runs through the area, and there are information boards where visitors can learn more about what life and the local landscape were like during the Iron Age. üá∏üá™ @europeanvolk

The George Inn, rebuilt in 1677, is London's only surviving galleried inn. Saved by the National Trust, the Grade 1 listed building was once a drinking den for William Shakespeare and Charles Dickens. The pub was formerly known as the George and Dragon, named after the legend of Saint George and the Dragon. It is possible that it was used for Elizabethan theatrical productions (Inn-yard theatre), as other galleried inns were. A pub has existed on the site since medieval times. In 1677, it was rebuilt after a serious fire destroyed most of Southwark. The medieval pub was situated next door to an inn where Chaucer set The Canterbury Tales. Later, the Great Northern Railway used the George as a depot and pulled down two of its fronts to build warehousing. Now just the south face remains. Charles Dickens visited The George, and referred to it in both Little Dorrit and Our Mutual Friend. @europeanvolk

cleaned_message: The Bride of Lammermoor by John Everett Millais The Bride of Lammermoor is a tragic and historical novel by Scottish author Walter Scott. Along with A Legend of Montrose, it forms the third series of Tales of My Host. The two books appeared on the same day, June 21, 1819, under the pseudonym Jedediah Cleishbotham. Written in special conditions (the author is seriously ill), The Bride of Lammermoor differs from Scott's other historical novels: the story is not connected to any event of national importance, the period is not coherently specified, no historical figure appears, the subiect is less didactic, the supernatural holds an unusual place, the threat of fate is omnipresent and the two main characters meet a tragic end. This is Walter Scott's darkest historical novel. The story takes place in Scotland in the late 17th or early 18th century. Secretly engaged, a young girl is put under terrible family pressure to break her vows and marry another man. She gradually descends into madness. This "story of love and death" inspired Donizetti's famous opera Lucia di Lammermoor in 1835. üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å≥Û†Å£Û†Å¥Û†Åø @europeanvolk

American [2nd] Confederacy [U.S. Civil War Confederacy] usage of the Pattern 1853 Enfield It has been estimated that a significant number exceeding 900,000 P53 Enfields were imported into the United States and played a crucial role in numerous key battles from the Battle of Shiloh in April 1862 to the Siege of Vicksburg in May 1863, and all the way through the final conflicts of 1865. This particular firearm garnered immense popularity among Confederate forces, as evident from a survey conducted by British officials during the early stages of the war concerning the armaments utilized by the Western Confederate Forces. The survey revealed that nearly 70% of soldiers were equipped with smoothbore arms such as the Model 1842 Springfield. However, as the war progressed, a subsequent survey indicated that the majority, over 75%, of Confederate soldiers had managed to acquire rifles, particularly the esteemed Pattern 1853 Enfield.

On this day: In 1895, the National Trust (for places of historic interest or Natural Beauty) was founded by the social reformers: Octavia Hill, Sir Robert Hunter, and Clergyman Hardwicke Rawnsley Its origins, however, lie in the Kyrle Society (named after John Kryle), which was formed in 1876 by Hill and her sister Miranda; alongside the conservational work provided by Hunter (the renowned solicitor to the Commons Preservation society) and Rawnsley (a commited naturalist who had campainged for the protection of the lake district). United, these three passionate and resolute individuals went on to design and create one of the largest heritage sites in Britain; one which has guaranteed the survival of estates once victim to militant industrialisation and urbanisation: ensuring that the soil of Britain remains well protected and nurtured. Conserving the rich past of Britain, for all its people to embellish and appreciate to the upmost degree. Let's hope that it's stays true to its founding promise.
Katarzyna Figura in the film Przeznaczenie, 1983 üáµüá± @europeanvolk

On this day: In 1879, the Anglo-Zulu war started between the British Empire and the Zulu Kingdom. Inspiration from the North America Act of 1867 that formed the Candaian federation, convinved lord Carnarvon (secretary of state for the Colonies) that such an ordeal could and must take place in Africa. These interests led to Sir Bartle Frere being sent to South Africa as Lord Commisoner in 1874 in order to carry out the Empire's desire for conquest. Frere, on his initiative, sent a rather provactive ultimatum to the Zulu King Cetshwayo; and once rejected by the King, an invasion soon followed. War had been declared. The war is notable for several particularly bloody battles, including an opening victory of the Zulu at the Battle of Isandlwana, followed by the defence of Rourke's drift by a small British Garrison from an attack by a large Zulu force. The British eventually won the war, ending zulu dominace in the region.The Zulu Kingdom was made a protectorate and later annexed by the British Empire in 1887

On this day: In 871, West Saxon forces led by King √Üthelred and his brother Alfred (King Alfred the great) successfully defeated the invading Viking forces led by Bagsecg and Haldan at the battle of Ashdown. The battle was fierce, and the west saxon army suffered heavy losses against the imposing Vikings. However, √Üthelred, under major risk of being flanked by overwhelming Viking forces, decided to carry out a preemptive attack and led his men in a charge up hill. Soon battle eschewed and raged around a small thorn tree and, finally, the west saxons were victorious. Yet, Ashdown was a short-lived victory, as it was followed by two defeats, one at Basing and the other at Meretun. Luck worsened, as soon after Easter, which fell on 15 April that year, √Üthelred died and was succeeded by his brother Alfred. Finally, although the location of Ashdown is not known, the battle is usually thought to have occurred at Kingstanding Hill, South Oxfordshire: a claim that is frequently disputed by other historians.

On this day: In 1720, Charles Edward Stuart (popularly known as Bonnie Prince Charles) was born in Rome to the exiled stuart court. As the grandson of the deposed King James II, Charles was thought by many - especially Catholics, Scotsmen, and Irishmen - to be the true and legitimate claiment to the British throne. After being raised and educated in Italy, Charles, in 1744, travelled to France to take part in a planned invasion to restore the Stuart Monarchy under his father (James Francis Edward Stuart). When the French invasion fleet was partly wrecked by storms, Charles resolved to proceed to scotland after discussion with leading Jacobites. These talks resulted in Charles landing by ship on the west coast of Scotland, leading to the events that would start the Jacobite rising of 1745. Contrary to popular opinion, the early stages of the rising were all but in the favour of the Jacobites; with Charles' forces winning the crucial battles of Prestonpans (September 1745) and Falkirk Muir (January 1745). However, by April 1746, Charles' forces were defeated at the battle of Culloden, which effectively ended the Jacobite cause. While there were subsequent attempts, such as the planned French invasion in 1759, Charles was unable to restore the Stuart dynasty. With the Jacobite Cause lost, Charles continued his life in exile, living in France and later in Italy. He died in Roman,1788 (aged 67)

Woolwich London SE18 in 1937. Now I don't know Woolwich at all, but I found this photo on the Internet with no mention of where in Woolwich it was taken. OK the traffic pointer signs helped immensely, and after looking at a map I discovered that it was taken at the crossroads on Woolwich High Street, looking down Hare Street. The Cameraman would have had his back to the Ferry Approach. I believe that the building on the right in the photo, then occupied by Burton's, may still be there. The Coronation of King George VI took place in 1937, so that must be why there are lots of decorations.

Navvy Mission Cottage, Bulwell, Nottingham Next door to the Navvy Mission Hut in Bulwell, Nottingham was this small white cottage - given over to use as a navvy lodging. The sign on the wall of the whitewashed cottage reads ' The Navvy Mission - Good Samaritan Home. One Night's Free Lodgings - Given Only To Navvies In Tramp'. It is then undersigned by David Smith - Missionary. A man stands outside the cottage door who may well be David Smith. A woman is captured in motion on the left of the picture, just about to pass a hole on the cottage's boundary wall. The actual Mission Hut can be seen on the right.

This bridge which was situated 30m west of the original London Bridge was designed by engineer John Rennie and built in the 1820s to replace an earlier 17th century bridge. It was officially opened on 1st August by William IV and Queen Adelaide and was 928 feet in length and 49 feet wide. In the 1920s it was discovered that the bridge's foundations were unstable and the east side of the bridge was lower than the west side. In 1962 the bridge was sold to fund the building of a new bridge. It was purchased by an American entrepreneur and was painstakingly reassembled in Lake Havasu City, Arizona to span the Bridgewater Channel canal.

The Northumbrian Role in the Gunpowder Plot üí£üî• It was a Warwickshire man, Robert Catesby, that led the group, and Yorkshireman Guy Fawkes that was the explosives expert. But it was Thomas Percy, the Constance of Alnwick Castle & the cousin to the Earl of Northumberland that was behind the finance and logistics. A tall, physically impressive man, Percy funded the group and secured the leases to a number of properties in London, one of which was the undercroft beneath the House of Lords, where the gunpowder was placed. The group planned to spark an uprising in the Midlands, but Percy remained in London, tasked with capturing the King‚Äôs son Prince Henry. With Fawkes captured and the plot exposed on November 5th, Percy fled to the Midlands and caught up with the others. Their time was up on November 8th though when the men were besieged in Holbeche House in Staffordshire by the Sheriff of Worcester. Percy and Catesby were killed by the same musket ball during the shootout.

Old Bull & Bush - N End Way, #Hampstead, #London, #NW3 7HE @OldBullandBush Records show that this very presentable, spacious, Grade II listed pub would have originally been a farmhouse in the 16450‚Äôs and would obtain a licence to sell ale by the 1720‚Äôs. The pub gave birth to a song made famous during a Victorian era of theatrical entertainment named 'Music Hall'. The song "Down at the old Bull and Bush"which dates somewhere in the early 1910‚Äôs was sung by Florrie Forde and can still be found online or even purchased on vinyl today. "Come, come, come and make eyes at me Down at the Old Bull and Bush, Come, come, drink some port wine with me, Down at the Old Bull and Bush, Hear the little German Band, Just let me hold your hand dear, Do, do come and have a drink or two Down at the Old Bull and Bush, Bush, Bush Come, come, come and make eyes at me" I can tell you form listening to the song, its a charm and the thought of anything happening to this pub with such a memory attached it makes me shudder.

Julian (Latin: Flavius Claudius Julianus; Greek: ·º∏ŒøœÖŒªŒπŒ±ŒΩœåœÇ Ioulianos; 331 ‚Äì 26 June 363) was Roman emperor from 361 to 363, as well as a notable philosopher and author in Greek. His rejection of Christianity, and his promotion of Neoplatonic Hellenism in its place, caused him to be remembered as Julian the Apostate in Christian tradition. Julian was the last non-Christian ruler of the Roman Empire, and he believed that it was necessary to restore the Empire's ancient Roman values and traditions in order to save it from dissolution. He purged the top-heavy state bureaucracy, and attempted to revive traditional Roman religious practices at the expense of Christianity. His attempt to build a Third Temple in Jerusalem was probably intended to harm Christianity rather than please Jews. Julian also forbade Christians from teaching and learning classical texts.

The sad story of the village of Tyneham Prior to 1943, Tyneham was a working Dorset village; a simple, rural community with a Post Office, church and school. Most inhabitants relied on farming and fishing for their livelihood. In November 1943 all 225 residents were served notice that they had just 28 days to leave as this peaceful village and 7,500 acres of surrounding heathland were to be commandeered by the War Office to help train allied troops. At Christmastime in 1943 the last residents left believing one day they could return. On the day of evacuation a letter, written by the villagers, was pinned to the church door. It pleaded: ‚ÄúPlease treat the church and houses with care. We have given up our homes, where many of us have lived for generations, to help win the war and keep men free. We shall return one day, and thank you for treating the village kindly." 1/2

The True Story of the Cragg Vale Coiners. Up in Yorkshire in the 1760s, the industrial revolution was steaming ahead at full pelt. The rich were getting richer, through the building of cotton mills and factories, while the poor grew poorer. Suffering ensued. There was great poverty, especially in the area of Cragg Vale, near Hebden Bridge, which was populated by weavers, land-workers and their families. A man named David Hartley ‚Äì known as ‚ÄúKing David‚Äù, and played by Socha ‚Äì came up with a Robin-Hood-esque idea: he would lead a gang of people who would counterfeit coins to bring money back to their community. His idea was to get coins locally from crooked officials, shop owners or publicans, then smelt the original metals with base ores. This could be done by what was known as ‚Äòclipping‚Äô: shaving the edges off coins and milling them, meaning the original coins were imperceptibly smaller, while the offcuts could then be used to make new counterfeit coins, some of which were European, that then had the official designs stamped onto them. These coins were then placed back into circulation, and, according to the Yorkshire Examiner: ‚ÄúBy the end of the 1760s, approximately ¬£3.5m (¬£515m in today's money) of Coiner-forged coins had been paid into the Bank of England. The effect on the British economy was disastrous, devaluing the Pound by 9 percent.‚Äù The scheme continued successfully for almost 10 years, as the moors and vales of Cragg Vale were a relatively isolated place compared to the bigger cities in England. Clipping was a treasonous offence punishable by death and by 1769, rumours began circulating in parliament about a group committing fraud in Yorkshire. A public official, William Dighton, was put on to the gang of coiners, which now numbered about 80 people. One of the counterfeit coiners, James Broadbent, betrayed the group and gave evidence that revealed the conspirators in exchange for leniency of his own crimes. Dighton then arrested Hartley, which enraged his brother, Isaac. He rallied a gang of men who conspired to kill Broadbent (and in probably one of the earliest forms of crowdsourcing, raised 100 guineas from people who supported the plan) and on 10 November, 1769, two farm workers, Matthew Normanton and Robert Thomas, fatally shot Broadbent. The punishment The Marquess of Rockingham (and also former Prime Minister) Charles Watson-Wentworth was charged with finding the murderers, and by Christmas day of that same year, he had arrested 30 coiners. This is where The Gallows Pole name comes in: David Hartley was hanged at York Tyburn on April 28, 1770. Broadbent‚Äôs murderers were both hanged as well: Thomas on August 6, 1774 and Normanton on April 15, 1775. Hartley‚Äôs brother, Isaac, managed to escape, and lived until 1815.

On masculinity: a critical analysis Preliminary: what is gender? In order to analyse what masculinity means and has denoted historically, we must first analyse the concept of 'gender' and whether or not it is synonymous with 'sex'. Sex is easy to define. I.e a biological taxonomy that denotes whether a specimine is female or male, based purely on the corresponding reproductive parts. However, gender is more complex. As for the sake of argument and utility, gender refers to the psychological aspect of a biological organisms corresponding sex. I.e Masculinity corresponds with being male, vice versa conceding females. Yet due to the abnormalities present in psychological behaviours, one could best describe gender as being the normative behaviours corresponding to the sex of the organism. While this seems to resolve the issue, one must remember that due to a series of reasons one may not behave in a way that is the norm for their sex Hence why a biological male can show stronger signs of a feminine gender, yet still be a man. This could explain why many ancient cultures viewed being a man or woman as requiring a journey of becoming. As one can be born a female yet act with a masculine disposition, a disposition that illsuits womanhood. This might also explain why some cultures had a conception of a third gender, one in which the disparity between the biological sex and psychological gender of a certain individual is too great for them to be considered a man or woman respectfully. One cannot shrugg of these issues either, as hiding a problem usually makes it worse. Otherwise, we end up where we are currently, where absurdity reigns under the false tag of acceptance by individuals that care nothing for reason or truth. In conclusion, sex is a biological denotation of an organism, while gender is the psychological denotation of the behavious that normally corresponde with each sex. >#OnMasculinity

Mick Meany, a 33 year old Irish builder, peers from a supply hole from his modified coffin, laid out upstairs at the Admiral Nelson pub in Kilburn, North London. He is training for an attempt at the world record for the longest time spent underground. He would be supplied with food, newspapers and books through a 6 inch pipe. Those dearest to him tried but ultermately proved in vain, to talk him out of his quest, telling him that he was digging his own grave and that he had lost the plot. He would go on to achieve his goal, 61 days under a builder's yard in Kilburn. Upon his death he was cremated close to where he achieved his world record. 19th February, 1968. Photo by Chris Ware.

Bird market, London, 1890s. Caged birds in Sclater Street, London, UK. The shop is that of James Morris, naturalist and dealer in animals 'from a humming bird to an elephant'. The shop claims to have been established for over 50 years. Sclater Street was famous for having a bird market every Sunday. Farringdon Street with Holborn Viaduct in the distance, 1890. On the right is Oriel House occupied by Marcus Ward & Co Limited, an international printing and publishing firm. The company had its origins in Belfast in 1802 and opened a London office in Covent Garden in 1867 with these premises at 30-31 Farringdon Street housing the firm from 1884. After almost a century of printing and publishing, they ran into difficulties and the business closed down in 1899. The building suffered bomb damage in the Second World War and was demolished being replaced with Lexis House.

url_description: Sabbione in Switzerland is a real life hobbit town. This quirky Swiss village has buildings that remind of Hobbiton, the hobbit town in the movie Lord of the Rings. It is a short drive from Locarno and Ascona. The famous village Foroglio is only minutes away and definitely worth a visit. url_description: It's chilly morning for a couple who are heading out to a wedding. The date is March 14th 1775, an important year in American history but just another day in the lives of many. How did these people dress? How did they shave or even brush their teeth? Things that we take for granted today looked completely different 250 years ago. Today we'll try on beautiful clothing from our old friends, Samson Historical. You can find their shop here: https://www.samsonhistorical.com/ Samson also has a thorough cataloge with full color photos. You can request for one to be sent to your residence from their website here: https://www.samsonhistorical.com/pages/2022-catalog Samson offers a wide range of goods that can be used in both a modern and a historical setting. They offer men and women's clothing, home furnishings including blankets and pottery. Shooting supplies, tradtionally crafted glass bottles, personal care, men and womne's footware, leather goods and care, teas, iron cookware, redware and so much more. I am often asked where I obtain my historically accurate equipment and honestly most of it comes from Samson! Once you browse their site you may recgonize some of their goods that I use in my cabin. Whenever I order from them I recieve my package within 3 days too which is excellent. I can't recomend them enough for those seeking traditional craftsmenship. All of the cosmetics and toiletries, minus the shaving equipment and soap, were purchased from Littlebits on Etsy. Her shop specilizes in recreating historical toiletries using real period recipes. https://www.etsy.com/shop/LitttleBits?ref=simple-shop-header-name&listing_id=701059995

City Arms, 5 Little Saffron Hill, Charterhouse EC1 Charterhouse pubs history index At 5 Little Saffron Hill by 1910 Saffron Hill takes its name from the saffron which was once grown here on land owned by the Bishops of Ely. The land laid on an embankment of the western edge of the River Fleet. Saffron was used in the Middle Ages to disguise the taste of rancid meat and would have likely to have had a ready market in the nearby Smithfield live meat market. John Gerard was a skilled herbalist who lived in the area, carefully tended his garden, and in 1596 published a list of all the plants that grew there. The Herball or Generall Historie of Plants was the first catalogue of any one garden, public or private. (Although some scholars claim that the original book was essentially a translation of a popular earlier Flemish herbal.) In the late 1930s Little Saffron Hill was renamed Herbal Hill after Gerard‚Äôs work. From light heart to light pockets: Saffron Hill later became an evil slum, and features in Oliver Twist: ‚Äúin an obscure parlour, of a low public-house, in the filthiest part of Little Saffron Hill‚Ä¶sat, brooding over a little pewter measure and a small glass‚Ä¶Mr William Sikes‚Äù. A little snippet from a book. Opposite our house was a timber yard that was infested with rats. On the 28th December 1879 the Tay Bridge disaster occurred. 75 passengers were killed when the structure collapsed under a train during a storm. The subsequent inquiry found that the bridge's designer, Thomas Bouch, had not made sufficient allowance for wind pressure and that the contractor had used imperfect metal castings. Bouch was widely blamed for the tragedy and died of ill health brought on by his ordeal shortly thereafter. The foundations of the collapsed bridge can still be seen today as one crosses the Tay on its replacement.

The Boy On The Moor by Annette Von Droste Hulshoff 'Tis an eerie thing o'er the moor to fare When the eddies of peat-smoke justle, When the wraiths of mist whirl here and there And wind-blown tendrils tussle, When every step starts a hidden spring And the trodden moss-tufts hiss and sing 'Tis an eerie thing o'er the moor to fare When the tangled reed-beds rustle. The child with his primer sets out alone And speeds as if he were hunted, The wind goes by with a hollow moan-- There's a noise in the hedge-row stunted. 'Tis the turf-digger's ghost, near-by he dwells, And for drink his master's turf he sells. "Whoo! whoo!" comes a sound like a stray cow's groan; The poor boy's courage is daunted. Then stumps loom up beside the ditch, Uncannily nod the bushes, The boy running on, each nerve a twitch, Through a jungle of spear-grass pushes. And where it trickles and crackles apace Is the Spinner's unholy hiding-place, The home of the curs√®d Spinning-witch Who turns her wheel 'mid the rushes. On, ever on, goes the fearsome rout, In pursuit through that region fenny, At each wild stride the bubbles burst out, And the sounds from beneath are many. Until at length from the midst of the din Comes the squeak of a spectral violin, That must be the rascally fiddler lout Who ran off with the bridal penny! The turf splits open, and from the hole Bursts forth an unhappy sighing, "Alas, alas, for my wretched soul!" 'Tis poor damned Margaret crying! The lad he leaps like a wounded deer, And were not his guardian angel near Some digger might find in a marshy knoll Where his little bleached bones were lying. But the ground grows firmer beneath his feet, And there from over the meadow A lamp is flickering homely-sweet; The boy at the edge of the shadow Looks back as he pauses to take his breath, And in his glance is the fear of death. 'Twas eerie there 'mid the sedge and peat, Ah, that was a place to dread, O!

Earl Shilton castle was built in the mid 1100s by Robert de Beaumont, 2nd Earl of Leicester. It was a motte and bailey castle and was built near the site of St Peters Chapel, which is no longer standing. The motte is 50 metres in diameter, with the south side being 3 metres high and the north being 1.5 metres high. No attacks were recorded on Earl Shilton during the English civil war of 1135-1153. The castle stood for around 40 years before being mostly destroyed and later converted into a hunting lodge. The only reminder of the 12th century castle are the earthworks. The nearby church of St Simon & St Jude was rebuilt in the 1850s with some of the stones from the hunting lodge. The boundary of the church walls is assumed to be the sight of the bailey. What we see standing today is a 19th century replica of what the gatehouse may have looked like.

Here be dragons! In recent times the White Dragon became a symbol of English ethnicity. The OE word for dragon was draca and places where dragons dwelled, upon their gold-hoards, still bear the name drake. In Godalming, that part of Surrey home to many heathen sites, we find a Drakehill or Dragon hill. Drake North in Wiltshire was once √æes dracenhorde or the dragon's hoard. As one would expect, dragons slept in barrows leaving us many place names which reflect this - Dragley in Ulverton was once spelt Drakelow meaning dragon's mound. We also find a Drakelow in Bedfordshire, Derbyshire and Worcestershire. In Surrey Dragberry was once Drakeberghe (OE draca + beorg) again meaning the dragon's mound. Pictured above is one of the most famous dragon hills in England, Dragon Hill near the Uffington white horse.

Anglo-Saxon swords were not merely death-dealing weapons, ‚Äòwigena weor√∞mynd‚Äô (‚Äújoy of warriors‚Äù (Beowulf 1559) but potent symbols of leadership, social status and ancestral lineage. Oaths of fealty and maybe even marriage vows were sworn on the sword, probably to invoke the power of the sword-god Tiw, who protected the sanctity of oaths. The 10th Century Exeter Book contains numerous Anglo-Saxon Riddles; two of which clearly have a sword as the solution. In her seminal book on the Anglo-Saxon sword, HR Ellis Davidson discusses the sword-riddles in some detail. In light of previous discoveries; particularly that of the Staffordshire Hoard, the Sword Riddles are well worth re-examining.

cleaned_message: The Phoenix and the Turtle - William Shakespeare (Daily poem#03) Let the bird of loudest lay, On the sole Arabian tree, Herald sad and trumpet be, To whose sound chaste wings obey. But thou, shrieking harbinger, Foul pre-currer of the fiend, Augur of the fever's end, To this troop come thou not near. From this session interdict Every fowl of tyrant wing, Save the eagle, feather'd king: Keep the obsequy so strict. Let the priest in surplice white, That defunctive music can, Be the death-divining swan, Lest the requiem lack his right. And thou, treble-dated crow, That thy sable gender mak'st With the breath thou giv'st and tak'st, 'Mongst our mourners shalt thou go. Here the anthem doth commence: Love and constancy is dead; Phoenix and the turtle fled In a mutual flame from hence. So they lov'd, as love in twain Had the essence but in one; Two distincts, division none: Number there in love was slain. Hearts remote, yet not asunder; Distance, and no space was seen 'Twixt the turtle and his queen; But in them it were a wonder. So between them love did shine, That the turtle saw his right Flaming in the phoenix' sight: Either was the other's mine. Property was thus appall'd, That the self was not the same; Single nature's double name Neither two nor one was call'd. Reason, in itself confounded, Saw division grow together; To themselves yet either-neither, Simple were so well compounded. That it cried how true a twain Seemeth this concordant one! Love hath reason, reason none If what parts can so remain. Whereupon it made this threne To the phoenix and the dove, Co-supreme and stars of love; As chorus to their tragic scene. THRENOS. Beauty, truth, and rarity. Grace in all simplicity, Here enclos'd in cinders lie. Death is now the phoenix' nest; And the turtle's loyal breast To eternity doth rest, Leaving no posterity:- 'Twas not their infirmity, It was married chastity. Truth may seem, but cannot be: Beauty brag, but 'tis not she; Truth and beauty buried be. To this urn let those repair That are either true or fair; For these dead birds sigh a prayer. >> Click here for the previous poem >> #thedailypoem

The question of mathematics Part.1 - Introduction. A subject that has always remained dear and close, one to which I am most proficient and well versed in, yet rarely discuss in conversation: I am of course referring to mathematics, especially to its most sublime form, pure mathematics. To me and as to other great mathematicians, the subject is but the definition of pure reason, an abstract study that attempts to describe the facets of reality either by conceptualising abstract quantities from empirical finding (Applied) or from rationalised axioms (Pure). As such, mathematics is more then mere counting, and consists of four main topic areas and one Meta-Mathematical area. These being as follows: numbers (arithmetic and number theory), formulas and related structure (geometry and or topology), and quantities and their changes ( Calculus and analysis). With meta-mathematics consisting of Logic and set theory that attempt to solve, prove and deduce the axiomatic and theoretical proofs of mathematics as whole. As such, the mathematician uses a variety of methods to prove, categorise and periodically stage the steps of the branches. With mathematical proofs serving as the Pure staging of deductive rules from previous axioms, formulas or sequences to further construct wider rules of concerning abstract concepts: example being Euler‚Äôs Identity. While mathematical models serve as the applied staging of theories constructed around empirically backed data used most often in: physics, statistics,economics, finance,psychology and etc. Example: The motion equations that describe the prescribed movement and temporal displacement and distances of a moved object in a plane. The upcoming parts will continue to explain in thorough detail the structure, problems and questions all relating to this great and bountiful subject #Thequestionofmathematics Part.1

cleaned_message: George Frideric (or Frederick) Handel baptised Georg Friedrich H√§ndel,23 February 1685‚Äì 14 April 1759. He was a German-British Baroque composer well known for his operas, oratorios, anthems,concerti grossi, and organ concertos. Handel received his training in Halle and worked as a composer in Hamburg and Italy before settling in London in 1712, where he spent the bulk of his career and became a naturalised British subject in 1727. He was strongly influenced both by the middle-German polyphonic choral tradition and by composers of the Italian Baroque. In turn, Handel's music forms one of the peaks of the "high baroque" style, bringing Italian opera to its highest development, creating the genres of English oratorio and organ concerto, and introducing a new style into English church music. He is consistently recognized as one of the greatest composers of his age. Here is an article analysing only a handful of his greatest works. https://t.me/theorcheatraCM

Oscar-Claude Monet:(14 November 1840 ‚Äì 5 December 1926) was a French painter and founder of impressionist painting who is seen as a key precursor to modernism, especially in his attempts to paint nature as he perceived it. During his long career, he was the most consistent and prolific practitioner of impressionism's philosophy of expressing one's perceptions before nature, especially as applied to Plein air (outdoor) landscape painting. The term "Impressionism" is derived from the title of his painting Impression,soleil Levant, exhibited in the 1874 ("exhibition of rejects") initiated by Monet and his associates as an alternative to the Salon. https://t.me/TheAthenaeumTRR

How, while he hid from Sir Thomas's keepers, Crouched in a ditch and drenched by the midnight Dews, he had listened to gipsy Juliet Rail at the dawning. A Harrington jacket (originally known only as a Baracuta jacket or a G9) is a lightweight, waist-length jacket made of cotton, polyester, wool or suede. Designs often incorporate traditional Fraser tartan or checkerboard-patterned lining The first Harrington-style jackets were claimed to be made in the 1930s by the British clothing company, Baracuta.Baracuta's original design, the G9, is still in production. The British company Grenfell, previously known as Haythornthwaite and Sons, also claims to have invented an identical jacket around the same time based on their golf jackets which is also still in production using their own signature cotton. The Harrington from either original source is based on lightweight, roomy jackets worn to play golf hence the G in the G4 or G9 naming convention for Baracuta. Both versions were originally made in Lancashire, England..

The commercial production of Basque-style berets began in the 17th century in the Oloron-Sainte-Marie area of southern France. Originally a local craft, beret-making became industrialised in the 19th century. The first factory, Beatex-Laulhere, claims production records dating back to 1810. The Battle of Lepanto ‚Äì 7 October 1571 The Battle of Lepanto was a naval engagement that took place when a fleet of the Holy League, a coalition of Catholic states arranged by Pope St. Pius V, inflicted a major defeat on the fleet of the Ottoman Empire in the Gulf of Patras. The navel engagement marked a decisive victory for Christendom, pushing back the Ottoman Empire from expanding into the Mediterranean and halted their advance into Italian controlled territories and any possibility of besieging Rome itself. Amidst overwhelming odds and rowing against the winds, Our Lady interceded and the winds turned in the favour of the Holy League and so the battle was won. The victory was credited to the Blessed Virgin Mary, whose intercession with God they had implored through the recitation of the Rosary. Pope St. Pius V had requested the faithful to pray the Rosary unceasingly for triumph in this decisive battle. Churches were kept open and the soldiers fasted and prayed the Rosary before the fight.
